“Mr Lloyd Thornhill (Captain of the C&B Crown Cordaans) and I are sitting on a busy Wednesday afternoon in late January at the pan yard. The heat is tremendous. Pupils of the neighbouring Bon Accord Primary School walk past the pan yard in effervescent groups; oblivious to its growing historical and social significance to the community. The traffic is at a standstill but grows louder and impatient. Adult voices can now be heard shouting and swearing at each other. But somewhere in the chaos, a distinct pitch is heard. It is slow and sweet like the red syrup dripping down the pupils’ hands. It emerges louder and faster and at last; the two musicians are pleased with the outcome of their private rehearsal.  “The history of this small Tobago conventional band is rooted in the development of the Western peninsula of the island. In fact, its name is what is known as a portmanteau – a combination of two or more words and their meanings. In this instance, Mr Thornhill advises me that the name Crown Cordaans represents the vibrant commercial districts of Crown Point, Canaan and Bon Accord. Sadly however, the band has been seemingly omitted from most of the meaningful fiscal development that is associated with these areas.  “Crown Cordaans is a relatively new band with an old soul. To appreciate the achievements of C&B Crown Cordaans it is important to reflect on the history of steel bands in the area. According to Mr Thornhill, Old Oak Starlift was the first steel band in the community. In the late 1960’s however, a faction of the band organised themselves into another group which was known as the BP Serenaders. It was in 1966 that Mr Thornhill (then twenty-four years old) experienced his first National panorama as a member of BP Serenaders. He recalls that both bands competed that year.
